Phillip Knightley shows in The First Casualty how, during the American civil war, the Crimean war, the Boer war, the First World War, the Spanish civil war, the Abyssinian war, the Second World World War, the Korean war and Vietnam, press freedom was ever the first state victim.
But the media were always willing. Such celebrated correspondents as John Gunther, W. B. Yeats, Robert Ruark and Ernest Hemingway readily agreed to follow government lines.A 1982 TV Review edition revealed how the big newspapers, notably The New York Times, at James Reston's insistence, willingly gave up their pages to President John F. Kennedy during Cuba's Bay of Pigs crisis of 1961-2.
William Rivers reports, in The Other Government, that journalists acted as Lyndon Johnson's chief f1acks in Vietnam. In a piece called A Letter to My Daughter, published by Parade on May 2, 1982, Halberstam relates the lies that MargueriteHiggins told of him as a "Vietcong" sympathiser.
After the 1975 Angolan crisis, in which such correspondents as David Lamb and Sanford Ungar had churned out the vilest lies about Soviet, Cuban and East German mischief, Henry Kissinger finally admitted that AP and UPI had willingly used CIA agentsas correspondents.



